> Lime, avocado, and cilantro are familiar ingredients in a taco, bringing tartness, 
> creaminess, and herby overtones, respectively. You don't expect sweetness inside a 
> tortilla, however, which we snuck in with these honey-coated shrimp. But what a 
> pleasant surprise the sticky stuff is: it leaves the filling dripping with succulent 
> juices that are boosted by citrus and a smidge of optional chili heat.

Wash and dry all produce. Zest one @lime{1} until you have 1 tsp zest, then cut into 
halves. Cut remaining @lime{1} in half, then cut one half into wedges. Peel, halve, 
and thinly slice @red onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Halve, pit, and thinly 
slice @avocado{1/2}(halved and thinly sliced). Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%oz}(roughly chopped).

Add @shredded red cabbage{8%oz}, @sour cream{6%tbsp}, juice from one lime half, and 
a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch} to a #medium bowl{}. Toss until combined.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. 
Add onion and season with salt and pepper. Cook, tossing occasionally, until softened 
and starting to brown, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Meanwhile, rinse @shrimp stir-fry{20%oz} and pat dry with a #paper towel{}. Once onions 
are browned, add shrimp and @chili flakes{1%tsp}(to taste) to pan. Season with salt 
and pepper. Cook, tossing, until shrimp start to turn pink, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir in 
juice from 2 remaining lime halves, lime zest, and @honey{2%tsp}. Cook, stirring, until 
shrimp are cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Wrap @flour tortillas{12} in a damp paper towel and microwave on high until warm, 
about ~{30%seconds}.

> TIP: Alternatively, wrap tortillas in foil and warm in oven for 5 minutes at 425 degrees.

Fill each tortilla with shrimp mixture, slaw, avocado, and cilantro. Serve with lime 
wedges on the side for squeezing over.